1919 and 1921, priests had to define their position anew.Using a wealth of source material, much of it newly available, this book assesses the clergy’s response to political violence. It describes how the image of shared victimhood at the hands of the British helped to contain tensions between the clergy and the republican movement, and shows how the links between Catholicism and Irish nationalism were sustained.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aHISTORY / Europe / Ireland.2bisacsh  aBlack and Tans.  aCatholicism.  aIRA.  aconfession.  amorality.  apriests.  arepublicans.  asermons.  aviolence.1 aHeffernan, Brian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2016 eBook-Packagez978311128282440uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152611797740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526117977423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526117977/original  a978-3-11-128282-4  Manchester University Press 2016 eBook-Packageb2016  aGBV-deGruyter-alles